,"Simona Stoyanova","SS","https://orcid.org/0000-0003-3914-9569",{"_":183,"when":184,"who":168},"Jonathan Prag made initial edit from publications","2022-01-30",[],[187],"Ansaldi, 1851, I monumenti dell'antica Centuripi",[189],"9BF3BJJI",[191,192,193,20,26,30,194,195,196,197,195,198,99],"isic002950","i.sicily inscription 002950",{"_":5},"centuripae","centuripe","italy","sicily","ancient greek",[],{"title":201,"body":202,"divs":203,"editions":228,"images":238,"handnote":239},"ISic002950. I.Sicily inscription 002950","\u003Cdiv id=\"editions\">\u003Cdiv class=\"attribution\">Unknown\u003C/div>\u003Cdiv id=\"edition-interpretive\" lang=\"grc\">  \u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang=\"grc\">\u003Cspan class=\"ab\" id=\"div-interpretive\"> (Ansaldi reports that the text recorded a gymnasiarch by the name of Cornelius, and indicated in some fashion that it had been set up in front of the gymnasium) \u003C/span>\u003C/div>  \u003Cp class=\"miniapp\">\u003C/p>\u003C/div>\u003Cdiv class=\"attribution\">Unknown\u003C/div>\u003Cdiv id=\"edition-diplomatic\" lang=\"grc\">\u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang=\"grc\">\u003Cspan class=\"ab\" id=\"div-diplomatic\">(Ansaldi reports that the text recorded a gymnasiarch by the name of Cornelius, and indicated in some fashion that it had been set up in front of the gymnasium)\u003C/span>\u003C/div>\u003Cp class=\"miniapp\">\u003C/p>\u003C/div>\u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"facsimile-images\">\u003Ch2>Facsimile Images\u003C/h2>\u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"apparatus\">\u003Ch4>Apparatus criticus\u003C/h4>\u003Cul>\u003Cli>\u003Cspan>\u003Cspan>No copy of the text is preserved\u003C/span>\u003C/span>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>\u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"translation\">\u003Ch2> translation\u003C/h2>\u003Cp class=\"translation-author\">  \u003C/p>\u003Cp>  \u003C/p>\u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"commentary\">\u003Ch2>commentary\u003C/h2>  \u003Cp>A Greek inscription recording a gymnasiarch with the name Cornelius. It was seemingly lost even when Ansaldi reported it in 1851. It was apparentliy written in Greek, and the text indicated that it was erected in front of the gymnasium, and tha tthe gymnasiarch responsible was a Cornelius. Ansaldi laments its loss. Other texts record the existence of a gymnasium (ISic002945 and ISic004370), while a Latin text found elsewhere in the town (ISic000004) records the building of a sphaeristerium (part of a baths or gymnasium) by two Cornelii in the Imperial period. It is tempting to link the name Cornelius, at least to the same family, but there is no formal basis for doing so. The date of this text is clearly problematic, since the use of Greek suggests a pre-imperial date, while the name Cornelius encourages a date in the Imperial period (by comparison with other material). A date at the very end of the Republican period / beginning of the Augustan period is perhaps most likely.\u003C/p>  \u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"bibliography\">\u003Ch2>bibliography\u003C/h2>  \u003Cul>\u003Cli> Ansaldi 1851 \u003Ca href=\"http://arachne.uni-koeln.de/item/buchseite/724712\" target=\"_blank\">15-16\u003C/a>  \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002182\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002182\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>  \u003Cul>\u003Cli> Libertini 1926 75-76 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001874\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001874\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> Libertini 1949 93-94 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001865\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001865\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> Bivona 1970 cf. 004 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002142\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002142\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> Bivona 1970 22 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002142\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002142\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> Wilson 1990 152 fig.130 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001509\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001509\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>  \u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"handnote\"> Line 1    Interlineation line 1 to 2    \u003C/div>\u003Cdiv id=\"license\"> Licensed under a Creative Commons-Attribution 4.0 licence. \u003C/div>",[204,207,210,213,216,219,222,225],{"id":205,"html":206},"editions","\u003Cdiv class=\"attribution\">Unknown\u003C/div>\u003Cdiv id=\"edition-interpretive\" lang=\"grc\">  \u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang=\"grc\">\u003Cspan class=\"ab\" id=\"div-interpretive\"> (Ansaldi reports that the text recorded a gymnasiarch by the name of Cornelius, and indicated in some fashion that it had been set up in front of the gymnasium) \u003C/span>\u003C/div>  \u003Cp class=\"miniapp\">\u003C/p>\u003C/div>\u003Cdiv class=\"attribution\">Unknown\u003C/div>\u003Cdiv id=\"edition-diplomatic\" lang=\"grc\">\u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang=\"grc\">\u003Cspan class=\"ab\" id=\"div-diplomatic\">(Ansaldi reports that the text recorded a gymnasiarch by the name of Cornelius, and indicated in some fashion that it had been set up in front of the gymnasium)\u003C/span>\u003C/div>\u003Cp class=\"miniapp\">\u003C/p>\u003C/div>",{"id":208,"html":209},"facsimile-images","\u003Ch2>Facsimile Images\u003C/h2>",{"id":211,"html":212},"apparatus","\u003Ch4>Apparatus criticus\u003C/h4>\u003Cul>\u003Cli>\u003Cspan>\u003Cspan>No copy of the text is preserved\u003C/span>\u003C/span>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>",{"id":214,"html":215},"translation","\u003Ch2> translation\u003C/h2>\u003Cp class=\"translation-author\">  \u003C/p>\u003Cp>  \u003C/p>",{"id":217,"html":218},"commentary","\u003Ch2>commentary\u003C/h2>  \u003Cp>A Greek inscription recording a gymnasiarch with the name Cornelius. It was seemingly lost even when Ansaldi reported it in 1851. It was apparentliy written in Greek, and the text indicated that it was erected in front of the gymnasium, and tha tthe gymnasiarch responsible was a Cornelius. Ansaldi laments its loss. Other texts record the existence of a gymnasium (ISic002945 and ISic004370), while a Latin text found elsewhere in the town (ISic000004) records the building of a sphaeristerium (part of a baths or gymnasium) by two Cornelii in the Imperial period. It is tempting to link the name Cornelius, at least to the same family, but there is no formal basis for doing so. The date of this text is clearly problematic, since the use of Greek suggests a pre-imperial date, while the name Cornelius encourages a date in the Imperial period (by comparison with other material). A date at the very end of the Republican period / beginning of the Augustan period is perhaps most likely.\u003C/p>  ",{"id":220,"html":221},"bibliography","\u003Ch2>bibliography\u003C/h2>  \u003Cul>\u003Cli> Ansaldi 1851 \u003Ca href=\"http://arachne.uni-koeln.de/item/buchseite/724712\" target=\"_blank\">15-16\u003C/a>  \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002182\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002182\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>  \u003Cul>\u003Cli> Libertini 1926 75-76 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001874\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001874\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> Libertini 1949 93-94 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001865\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001865\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> Bivona 1970 cf. 004 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002142\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002142\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> Bivona 1970 22 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002142\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002142\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> Wilson 1990 152 fig.130 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001509\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001509\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>  ",{"id":22